</tableCitation>
revealed that the genera 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF88636761EFF59FFB67" box="[797,908,1164,1189]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" genus="Austinixa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40EF51413902FF88636761EFF59FFB67" box="[797,908,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Austinixa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF8863DB61EFF203FB67" box="[929,1040,1164,1189]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" genus="Glassella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40EF51413902FF8863DB61EFF203FB67" box="[929,1040,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Glassella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF88645F61EFF2A0FB67" box="[1061,1203,1164,1189]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" genus="Indopinnixa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40EF51413902FF88645F61EFF2A0FB67" box="[1061,1203,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Indopinnixa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF8864B261EFF330FB67" box="[1224,1315,1164,1189]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" genus="Pinnixa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40EF51413902FF8864B261EFF330FB67" box="[1224,1315,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Pinnixa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF88617261D7F797FB0F" box="[264,388,1204,1229]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" genus="Scleroplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40EF51413902FF88617261D7F797FB0F" box="[264,388,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Scleroplax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF8861B061D7F409FB0F" box="[458,538,1204,1229]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" genus="Tetrias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40EF51413902FF8861B061D7F409FB0F" box="[458,538,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Tetrias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be considered a presumed homogeneous group. All these taxa share at least two inclusive characters, including a distinct carapace that is wider than long and a conspicuous lobe on the outer margin of the basal segment on the exopod of the third maxilliped (
<figureCitation id="EAA091D63902FF8861AC604FF420FA84" box="[470,563,1324,1350]" captionStart="FIGURE 1. A – C" captionStartId="2.[264,367,1697,1721]" captionTargetBox="[330,1274,316,1683]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[311,1285,302,1691]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A – C Scleroplax granulata Rathbun, 1893 (female, cl 4.2 mm, cb 6.0 mm., El Coyote estuary, Abreojos Point, Baja California Sur, México, UABC); D) Pinnixa sp. (female, cb = 6.0 mm, El Verde estuary, Mazatlán, Sinaloa, México, EMU- 842; E) Auxtinixa cristata Rathbun, 1900, (male cb 6.3 mm., St. Lucie, Florida, USA, USNM). A, E) dorsal view; B) WL 1 – 4; C – D) MXP 3. Illustrations not to scale. Dotted lines indicate the setae of the propodus and dactylus. (E from Manning and Felder, 1989)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174460/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">
Fig 
<number id="C4539F743902FF886272604FF404FA84" box="[520,535,1324,1350]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="1.0">1</number>
C
</figureCitation>
–D, 
<number id="C4539F743902FF88621D604FF465FA84" box="[615,630,1324,1350]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
A–F). These novelties distinguish these genera within the 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF8861726037F7B9FAAC" box="[264,426,1364,1390]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pinnotheridae</taxonomicName>
and may represent a separate monophyletic assemblage. 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF8864336037F750FA54" authority="Glassell, 1938" authorityName="Glassell" authorityYear="1938" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" genus="Alarconia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40EF51413902FF8864336037F2AEFAAF" box="[1097,1213,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Alarconia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="160AF0A23902FF8864BF6037F750FA54" author="Glassell" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" refString="Glassell, S. A. (1938) New or little known crabs from the Pacific coast of northern Mexico. Transactions of the San Diego Society of Natural History, 8 (14), 91 - 106." type="journal article" year="1938">
Glassell, 
<number id="C4539F743902FF886172601FF750FA54" box="[264,323,1404,1430]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="1938.0">1938</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="160AF0A23902FF8861FD601FF4DBFA54" author="Campos" box="[391,712,1404,1430]" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" refString="Campos E. &amp; Wicksten, M. K. (1997) A new genus for the Central American crab Pinnixa costaricana Wicksten, 1982 (Crustacea: Brachyura: Pinnotheridae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 110 (1), 69 - 73." type="journal article" year="1997">
Campos &amp; Wicksten 
<number id="C4539F743902FF8862F6601FF4DBFA54" box="[652,712,1404,1430]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and the South Pacific genus 
<taxonomicName id="B59BF6D03902FF886440601FF437FA7C" authority="Milne Edwards &amp; Lucas, 1843" authorityName="Milne Edwards &amp; Lucas" authorityYear="1843" class="Malacostraca" family="Pinnotheridae" genus="Pinnotherelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="40EF51413902FF886440601FF2C9FA57" box="[1082,1242,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Pinnotherelia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="160AF0A23902FF88649E601FF437FA7C" author="Milne" pageId="4" pageNumber="41" refString="Milne Edwards, H. &amp; Lucas, H. (1843) Crustaces. In: D'Orbigny, A. Voyage dans l'Amerique meridionale (le Bresil, la republique orientale de l'Uruguay, la republique Argentine, la Patagonie, la republique du Chili, la republique du Bolivia, la republique du Perou) execute pendant les annees 1826, 1827, 1828, 1829, 1830, 1831, 1832 et 1833, 6 (1), 1 - 37, plates 1 - 17, Strasbourg." type="journal article" year="1843">
Milne Edwards &amp; Lucas, 
<number id="C4539F743902FF88619D60C7F437FA7C" box="[487,548,1444,1470]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="1843.0">1843</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, should not be considered members of this group despite sharing a carapace that is also wider than long. Both genera lack the exopod lobe of MXP 
<number id="C4539F743902FF88649860AFF2FCFA24" box="[1250,1263,1484,1510]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
. The systematics of these genera will be discussed elsewhere.
</paragraph>
